Following minutes of debate on the theme, members of the audience were invited to present their four-minute case in favour or against the motion, with about 20 people speaking in total.

Spenser Pinder and Pastor Barry Denmyer both spoke in favour of the motion, while Roland Einertson and Pastor John Joyner were the main speakers advocating for the negative side.

Pinder lauded the idea of a Man of the Year program and being bestowed honour by society. But he argued that “trendiness” often hindered objective worth for that honour.

“Society is very fickle and trending … when men of age, stature and influence, nothing greater than themselves become the [latest] means towards societal acclaim. They betray themselves. They demean themselves. They cause society to pay them homage. Nothing glorifying about that. But is this something that we should be rewarding as a Bahamian society?” Pinder said.

However, Einertson countered that awarding the country’s “greatest” something such as Man of the Year would allow The Bahamas to highlight some of the good things.

“Man of the Year is a small gesture that I don’t think will set us back … but will advance us forward … there are lots of things that we have done in this country over the years … that have driven us backwards and inhumane things we have done
